00:48:03.960 --> 00:48:05.495
"Thanks for Being Late."

00:48:05.495 --> 00:48:07.500
He deals with this issue.

00:48:07.500 --> 00:48:10.170
And he refers to one of
the two or three people

00:48:10.170 --> 00:48:12.600
that have been great
mentors with him.

00:48:12.600 --> 00:48:16.440
And this individual says we're
in a kind of the second round,

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:19.140
I guess, of a 15-round boxing
match or the second inning

00:48:19.140 --> 00:48:20.940
of a ninth-inning ballgame.

00:48:20.940 --> 00:48:24.060
The first inning was the
wonderful, remarkable,

00:48:24.060 --> 00:48:25.534
technological development.

00:48:25.534 --> 00:48:27.450
It took three centuries
for the printing press

00:48:27.450 --> 00:48:29.783
to reach a majority of the
population of Western Europe.

00:48:29.783 --> 00:48:32.724
It took the internet
between 1995 and 2005--

00:48:32.724 --> 00:48:34.390
less than a decade--
to reach a majority

00:48:34.390 --> 00:48:35.473
of the world's population.

00:48:35.473 --> 00:48:38.950
That, in itself, is a remarkable
technological accomplishment.

00:48:38.950 --> 00:48:41.580
But he said inning
two, or round two,

00:48:41.580 --> 00:48:43.440
is developing the
rules of the road

00:48:43.440 --> 00:48:47.490
with these dramatically new
and different tools that

00:48:47.490 --> 00:48:50.460
have great potential for
good, but also have potential

00:48:50.460 --> 00:48:51.540
for harm.

00:48:51.540 --> 00:48:55.500
And I guess as the internet
came along, some of us

00:48:55.500 --> 00:48:57.060
were of the view,
let this market be

00:48:57.060 --> 00:48:59.280
as free as it possibly
can be so that you

00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:01.050
don't stifle innovation.

00:49:01.050 --> 00:49:05.110
And then you say, mmm,
maybe there are some rules.

00:49:05.110 --> 00:49:07.440
But the rules, I think,
would be best developed

00:49:07.440 --> 00:49:10.530
from within these
industries, from people

00:49:10.530 --> 00:49:14.310
like yourselves who understand
not only current practices,

00:49:14.310 --> 00:49:18.480
but the practices to come,
rather than governments

00:49:18.480 --> 00:49:19.770
doing the whole job.

00:49:19.770 --> 00:49:21.690
And of course,
ideally, what you will

00:49:21.690 --> 00:49:26.160
have is the thoughtful people
in the industry identifying

00:49:26.160 --> 00:49:28.290
the problems now, and the
problems that will come,

00:49:28.290 --> 00:49:29.910
and solutions, and
where government

00:49:29.910 --> 00:49:31.720
is necessary to
have government act.

00:49:31.720 --> 00:49:35.040
But it's not it's the
government with the big stick,

00:49:35.040 --> 00:49:36.960
and they'll come along
and do the hitting,

00:49:36.960 --> 00:49:41.910
and meanwhile, the wrongs,
or the unfortunate practices,

00:49:41.910 --> 00:49:43.560
continue to grow
and grow and people

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:48.570
develop a distrust of the
ability of the people managing

00:49:48.570 --> 00:49:51.400
those enterprises to come up
with the rules of the road.

00:49:51.400 --> 00:49:53.850
You know, every
period in history

00:49:53.850 --> 00:49:55.170
has these big disruptions.

00:49:55.170 --> 00:49:59.640
And it takes thoughtfulness
to learn how to rejig.

00:49:59.640 --> 00:50:00.849
And the changes are enormous.

00:50:00.849 --> 00:50:03.098
But you think of the printing
press in Western Europe.

00:50:03.098 --> 00:50:05.160
That was resisted
for the longest time,

00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:07.972
because the Catholic
Church controlled religion.

00:50:07.972 --> 00:50:09.930
And the most important
thing in the Middle Ages

00:50:09.930 --> 00:50:12.630
to anyone in Western Europe
was your relationship with God.

00:50:12.630 --> 00:50:16.860
But that was managed
by a bureaucracy

00:50:16.860 --> 00:50:20.430
with a priest, bishop, cardinal,
and pope, and in a language

00:50:20.430 --> 00:50:21.840
that people didn't understand.

00:50:21.840 --> 00:50:25.620
And you certainly wouldn't
want to have them understand

00:50:25.620 --> 00:50:28.620
what the Bible said or
why you have the sacrament

00:50:28.620 --> 00:50:29.429
of holy communion.

00:50:29.429 --> 00:50:30.220
You do it in Latin.

00:50:30.220 --> 00:50:32.970
It's awe and mystery.

00:50:32.970 --> 00:50:37.980
And what happened with the
invention of the printing

00:50:37.980 --> 00:50:39.880
press-- it wasn't invented
in Western Europe.

00:50:39.880 --> 00:50:41.505
It was actually
invented in South Korea

00:50:41.505 --> 00:50:43.330
about 1,000 years before.

00:50:43.330 --> 00:50:45.780
But it didn't develop there--

00:50:45.780 --> 00:50:49.560
was people began to read
that truth for themselves.

00:50:49.560 --> 00:50:50.690
And they disintermediated.

00:50:50.690 --> 00:50:52.481
So they didn't need a
priest, and a bishop,

00:50:52.481 --> 00:50:54.840
and a cardinal, and
magnificent cathedrals.

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:56.830
And what happened
from that, of course,

00:50:56.830 --> 00:50:59.430
was not only did people
learn about the religion they

00:50:59.430 --> 00:51:01.620
felt important, but
they then realized

00:51:01.620 --> 00:51:03.840
how important education was.

00:51:03.840 --> 00:51:05.660
And that was the
breakdown of serfdom,

00:51:05.660 --> 00:51:07.310
the rise of the
cities in Europe,

00:51:07.310 --> 00:51:10.130
the Industrial Revolution,
the democratic institutions

00:51:10.130 --> 00:51:13.070
of parliament and so on,
and Europe leapt ahead

00:51:13.070 --> 00:51:15.650
of Islam, India,
and China, which

00:51:15.650 --> 00:51:19.220
were much more advanced
civilizations until about 1600,

00:51:19.220 --> 00:51:20.060
1700.

